{
  "answer": "**Charles Comte's strongest formulation** (from *Traité de Législation*, Vol. II): Climate exerts no influence on the fundamental physical traits or species characteristics that distinguish human varieties—\"the particular characteristics of each species [remain] the same in all latitudes\"—as evidenced by Europeans, Mongolians, and others retaining their features across continents and temperatures, from Hudson Bay to the Cape of Good Hope.[^1] While climate may modulate individual vigor or faculties *within* a species (e.g., weakening or strengthening them), it cannot \"efface the characteristic traits of species.\"[^2]\n\n**Charles Dunoyer's strongest formulation** (from *Nouveau traité d'économie sociale*, Vol. I): Climate and external circumstances cannot alter racial characters, which \"remain the same in all latitudes and in all climates\"; a single unmixed race stays identical under diverse conditions, while mixed races retain traits in the same locale (e.g., Americans red across America, Africans black from pole to equator).[^3] Race, not climate, primarily determines liberty and development capacity, though Dunoyer concedes some secondary role to \"external circumstances\" (quoting Comte approvingly but critiquing his emphasis).[^4]\n\n**Where they agree**: Both reject climate as a cause of *racial/species differences* or \"national character\" at the foundational level—racial traits are innate and immutable across climates, contra Montesquieu/Cabanis (e.g., no whitening of Negroes in cold Europe, no reddening of Europeans in tropics). Climate influences *individuals* or development *within* races but cannot produce or erase core traits.[^5]\n\n**Where Comte would say Dunoyer is overweighting climate**: Comte would likely critique Dunoyer's relative emphasis on \"external circumstances\" (climate/position) as a key modifier of development *beyond* race—e.g., Dunoyer's claim that favorable locales can \"compensate for the disadvantage of race,\" letting even inferior races outpace superiors if better situated (Europeans shipwrecked at the Cape would stagnate like Hottentots).[^6] Comte prioritizes invariant species traits and dedicates volumes to climate's *direct* effects on faculties (physical/intellectual/moral) within species, seeing position/climate as less compensatory than Dunoyer allows.[^7]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL II*, [Ch. 5/translation/#p-e2abd4](https://falsafa.corpus/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-ii-20331d/05-de-l-influence-attribuee-a-l-action-des-climats-su/translation/#p-e2abd4).\n\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL II*, [Ch. 5/translation/#p-1c04c9](https://falsafa.corpus/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-ii-20331d/05-de-l-influence-attribuee-a-l-action-des-climats-su/translation/#p-1c04c9); cf. Dunoyer's quote in Ch. 3, p-4d6d20.\n\n[^3]: Charles Dunoyer, *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL I*, [Ch. 2/translation/#p-d3fec5](https://falsafa.corpus/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-i-6da8ce/02-i-influence-de-la-race-sur-la-liberte/translation/#p-d3fec5).\n\n[^4]: Charles Dunoyer, *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL I*, [Ch. 3/translation/#p-0446c9](https://falsafa.corpus/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-i-6da8ce/03-ii-influence-des-circonstances-exterieures-sur-la-/translation/#p-0446c9).\n\n[^5]: Both cite fixed traits (Comte Ch. 4-5; Dunoyer Ch. 2 §2-3).\n\n[^6]: Charles Dunoyer, *Nouveau traité d'économie: VOL I*, [Ch. 3/translation/#p-4d6d20](https://falsafa.corpus/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-i-6da8ce/03-ii-influence-des-circonstances-exterieures-sur-la-/translation/#p-4d6d20).\n\n[^7]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL II*, Chs. 6-12 (e.g., [Ch. 6/translation/](https://falsafa.corpus/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-ii-20331d/06-des-difficultes-que-presente-la-question-de-l-infl/translation/)).",
